5C%22link%5C%22%3EFederal%20Reserve%20Bank%20of%20Dallas%3C%2Fa%3E%20noted%20last%20year%20this%20trends%20stems%20in%20part%20from%20the%20%26quot%3BGreat%20Resignation.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EDavid%20Autor%2C%20Ford%20Professor%20in%20the%20MIT%20Department%20of%20Economics%20who%20led%20the%20study%2C%20told%20Insider%20the%20labor%20market%20is%20becoming%20more%20competitive%20for%20low-wage%20workers.%20Better-paying%20firms%20are%20often%20the%20more%20productive%20firms%2C%20he%20said%2C%20so%20with%20more%20competition%2C%20workers%20have%20more%20agency%20to%20move%20to%20higher-paying%20ones%20maximizing%20productivity.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BIf%20competition%20for%20workers%20has%20increased%2C%20this%20isn't%20just%20good%20for%20workers%2C%20bad%20for%20employers%2C%26quot%3B%20Autor%20said.%20%26quot%3BIt%20also%20means%20the%20labor%20market%20is%20operating%20more%20efficiently%2C%20that%20workers%20are%20working%20in%20more%20productive%20firms%2C%20so%20it%20actually%20increases%20economic%20output.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EThe%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.americanbar.org%2Fgroups%2Fcrsj%2Fpublications%2Fhuman_rights_magazine_home%2Fwealth-disparities-in-civil-rights%2Famericas-vast-pay-inequality-is-a-story-of-unequal-power%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EAmerican%20Bar%20Association%20argued%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0strong%20jobs%20recovery%20and%20federal%20relief%20programs%20have%20given%20workers%20more%20bargaining%20power%2C%20allowing%20lower-wage%20workers%20to%20negotiate%20higher%20salaries%20or%20more%20easily%20leave%20positions%20in%20search%20of%20better-paying%20ones.%20Although%20low-wage%20workers%20have%20slightly%20narrowed%20the%20gap%2C%20corporate%20profits%20have%20boomed%2C%20allowing%20those%20at%20the%20very%20top%20to%20stay%20separated%20from%20the%20rest.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BWhat%20you%20really%20see%20in%202023%20is%20that%20a%20lot%20of%20workers%20either%20left%20because%20of%20the%20pandemic%20or%20just%20refused%20to%20take%20those%20jobs%2C%20and%20the%20highest%20job%20vacancy%20rates%20were%20in%20leisure%20and%20hospitality%2C%26quot%3B%20said%20Harry%20Holzer%2C%20John%20LaFarge%20Jr.%20SJ%20Professor%20of%20Public%20Policy%20at%20Georgetown%20University's%20McCourt%20School%20of%20Public%20Policy.%20%26quot%3BIn%20terms%20of%20old-fashioned%20supply%20and%20demand%2C%20employers%20faced%20a%20worker%20shortage%2C%20and%20it%20put%20pressure%20on%20them%20to%20raise%20wages.%26quot%3B%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHowever%2C%C2%A0those%20raises%20seem%20to%20have%20been%20short-lived%20and%20could%20be%20slowing%20down.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3ESince%20late%202022%2C%20though%2C%20wage%20growth%20for%20low-wage%20workers%20still%20exceeds%20that%20for%20high-wage%20workers%2C%20the%20gap%20is%20thinning%2C%20according%20to%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.atlantafed.org%2Fchcs%2Fwage-growth-tracker%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Edata%20from%20the%20Federal%20Reserve%20Bank%20of%20Atlanta%3C%2Fa%3E.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%20data-embed-type%3D%5C%22raw%5C%22%20data-type%3D%5C%22embed%5C%22%3E%3Cdiv%20data-embed-type%3D%5C%22raw%5C%22%20data-type%3D%5C%22embed%5C%22%3E%3Ciframe%20src%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fdatawrapper.dwcdn.net%2FnIwd7%2F1%2F%5C%22%20title%3D%5C%22Wage%20growth%20by%20wage%20level%5C%22%20data-external%3D%5C%221%5C%22%20height%3D%5C%22400%5C%22%3E%3C%2Fiframe%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%3Cp%3EIn%20June%202022%2C%20low-wage%20workers%20saw%207.2%25%20wage%20growth%20from%20the%20prior%20year%2C%20falling%20to%206.5%25%20in%20June%202023.%20Meanwhile%2C%20high-wage%20workers%20were%20at%20just%203.7%25%20year-over-year%20wage%20growth%20in%20June%202022%2C%20compared%20to%205.7%25%20in%20June%202023.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAnd%20while%20wage%20compression%20has%20helped%20narrow%20the%20gap%20between%20the%20bottom%20and%20top%20tiers%20of%20the%20vast%20majority%20of%20Americans%20who%20rely%20on%20employment%20for%20the%20bulk%20of%20their%20income%2C%20the%20very%20top%20of%20the%20spectrum%2C%20who%20instead%20make%20most%20of%20their%20money%20from%20investments%20in%20stocks%20or%20privately-held%20businesses%2C%20are%20%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Frealtimeinequality.org%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3Estill%20doing%20quite%20well%3C%2Fa%3E.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Ch2%3E'Moving%20the%20needle'%20on%20income%20inequality%3C%2Fh2%3E%3Cp%3E%3Ca%20rel%3D%5C%22noopener%5C%22%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.epi.org%2Fmultimedia%2Funequal-states-of-america%2F%5C%22%20target%3D%5C%22_blank%5C%22%3EAccording%20to%20the%20Economic%20Policy%20Institute%3C%2Fa%3E%2C%20the%20top%201%25%20of%20Americans%20make%20over%2026%20times%20more%20than%20the%20bottom%2099%25%20and%20hold%2021%25%20of%20the%20nation's%20total%20income.%C2%A0%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAutor%20said%20wage%20growth%20is%20more%20likely%20to%20plateau%20than%20continue%20its%20upward%20trajectory.%20With%20fewer%20young%20adults%20available%20for%20low-paid%20work%2C%20more%20people%20retiring%2C%20and%20increased%20consumption%20of%20goods%20and%20services%2C%20Autor%20expects%20the%20labor%20market%20to%20remain%20tight%20for%20another%20decade.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BThis%20phenomenon%20is%20not%20likely%20to%20just%20go%20back%20to%20where%20we%20were%20prior%20to%20the%20pandemic%20because%20we%20were%20already%20heading%20in%20the%20direction%20of%20tightening%20labor%20markets%20for%20the%20younger%20and%20less%20educated%20people%20who%20were%20willing%20to%20do%20physically%20demanding%20work%2C%26quot%3B%20Autor%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EAutor%20said%20higher%20minimum%20wages%2C%20more%20employment%20opportunities%20for%20non-college%20workers%20in%20sectors%20such%20as%20medicine%2C%20and%20eliminating%20tax%20subsidies%20for%20the%20elite%20could%20further%20chip%20away%20at%20inequality.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHolzer%20cautioned%20labor%20market%20tightness%20may%20diminish%20in%20the%20next%20few%20years%20with%20additional%20interest%20rate%20hikes%2C%20adding%20that%20AI%20may%20displace%20some%20lower-wage%20workers%20while%20enabling%20workers%20to%20pivot%20to%20more%20creative%20opportunities.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EHolzer%20said%20Biden%20initiatives%20such%20as%20the%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fus-building-factories-census-data-chips-act-inflation-reduction-act-2023-6%5C%22%3EInflation%20Reduction%20Act%20and%20the%20CHIPS%20Act%3C%2Fa%3E%C2%A0could%20help%20with%20job%20creation%20and%20training%2C%20though%20he%20anticipates%20the%20effects%20of%20such%20legislation%20will%20be%20modest.%20Some%20jobs%20in%20the%20fossil%20fuel%20industry%20may%20be%20replaced%20by%20green%20energy%20jobs%2C%20though%20not%20all%20regions%20or%20economic%20sectors%20may%20be%20impacted.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3E%26quot%3BFrom%20the%20vantage%20point%20of%20the%20whole%20economy%2C%20where%20it's%20at%20160%20million%20jobs%20and%20workers%2C%20it's%20hard%20for%20me%20to%20see%20that%20it%20moves%20the%20needle%20that%20much%2C%26quot%3B%20Holzer%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cp%3EWhat%20can%20move%20the%20needle%20more%2C%20he%20said%2C%20are%20gainful%20employment%20rules%20or%20student%20debt%20cancelation%20that%20make%20it%20easier%20for%20people%20to%20earn%20a%20degree%20for%20high-demand%20jobs.%20Policies%20that%20can%20nudge%20employers%20to%20create%20better%20jobs%2C%20expand%20workers%20getting%20profit%20sharing%2C%20and%20give%20workers%20more%20of%20a%20voice%20could%20also%20help%20close%20the%20income%20inequality%20gap%2C%20he%20said.%3C%2Fp%3E%3Cdiv%3ERead%20the%20original%20article%20on%20%3Ca%20href%3D%5C%22https%3A%2F%2Fwww.businessinsider.com%2Fthe-us-inequality-gap-is-quietly-getting-smaller-2023-7%5C%22%3EBusiness%20Insider%3C%2Fa%3E%3C%2Fdiv%3E%22%2C%22published%22%3A1690279201000%2C%22visual%22%3A%22https%3A%2F%2Fi.insider.com%2F64bec42ced4f460019622f77%3Fformat%3Djpeg%22%2C%22originID%22%3A%22htt